{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"cbdf1f7d-a61d-4745-8165-53eef962c928","content":"On macOS, when a process crashes the OS automatically generates a `.ips` crash report. You don't need `createdump`.\n\n**Where to find it:**\n\n- **User-level crashes:**\n  `~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`\n\n- **System-level crashes:**\n  `/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`\n\nLook for a file named like `YourAppName_YYYY-MM-DD-HHMMSS_machinename.ips`.\n\n**Quick command to find it:**\n```bash\nls -lt ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/*.ips | head -5\n```\n\n**Then what?**\n\nThe `.ips` file contains the native backtrace with addresses. You can:\n\n1. Open it in **Console.app** (built into macOS)\n2. View it in a text editor — it's JSON\n3. Symbolicate the .NET runtime frames using `atos` and debug symbols from the Microsoft symbol server\n\nIf you need help symbolicating the `.ips` file to get .NET runtime function names and source lines, I can invoke the **apple-crash-symbolication** skill.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"a5c37bd0-0e08-4275-9f6a-791b2c498a41","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app on macOS, without createdump available. This is a diagnostic question, not a code task. Let me answer directly from my knowledge.","outputTokens":340,"requestId":"D809:1E056F:61CF686:69B8493:69FBF021"},"id":"f5df8703-5965-4db9-919e-b1d863a60335","timestamp":"2026-05-07T01:51:38.716Z","parentId":"c1198977-f383-416d-9dca-fb71fec16a1b"}
